<br />
I buy a house for $100,000 of my own money. I get a mortgage on that house for $100,000 and buy another house for $100,000.<br />
<br />
The housing market then drops 10% all around the country, and my houses follow exactly.  Now each house is worth $90,000. 90k X 2 = 180,000. I sell one house for $90 and pay back the mortgage. I owe $10,000. I sell the other house for 90,000 leaving 80,000.<br />
<br />
I lost 20,000 out of the original 100,000. 20% which was the % value of the losses X my leverage or 10 * 2<br />
<br />
You can repeat it with more houses if you want. Say I lever up 10 times, getting 10 houses for my original amount of $100,000.<br />
<br />
The housing market rebounds 10% (which is what this Corzine guy was hoping would happen to Italian bonds, so watch). I now have 10 houses all worth $110,000. I sell them all, making $10,000 on 9 of them for 90,000 + $110,000 for the first house.  I made $200,000, double my money! (10 percent gain * 10 leverage = 100% or double my money)<br />
<br />
Had those bonds even risen 5% at 40X leverage, Corzine would have made a 200% return, tripling his original money. As fate would have it, they dropped and it put him under. <br><BR><font size=1>12:06 11-02-2011</font><BR><BR>I support the right of our troops to bear arms</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>Max of Tat </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Max of Tat '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont"><i>20% loss on their investments * 3 for leverage = 60%. Do the math, you&#39;ll see. </i><br />
<br />
But multiplication is commutative. <br />
<br />
A x .20 + B x .20 + C x .20 = (A + B + C) x .20<br />
<br />
NOT<br />
<br />
A x .20 + B x .20 + C x .20 = (A + B + C) x (3 x .20)<br />
<br />
I followed your example, but I don&#39;t see where the value became 40% of the investment.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
