<br />
Steps<br />
1) Italy issues $10 million dollars in bonds.<br />
2) A bunch of people buy them.<br />
3) The value of the bonds drops 10% based on fear over their taxes and spending. Say they are worth now 9 million.<br />
4) MF global buys $1.1 million in bonds for cheaper than face value for $1 million from their company coffers<br />
5) MF Global asks Enrique to borrow $800,000 and promises to give him their bonds as collateral. They&#39;ll pay him back in one month. He agrees<br />
6) Mf Global buys $900,000 of bonds for $800,000<br />
7) MF Global asks Neal to borrow $700,000 and promises to give him their new bonds as collateral. They&#39;ll pay him back in one month. He agrees<br />
8) Mf global buys $800,000 of bonds for $700,000<br />
9) MF Global asks Pat Sullivan to borrow $600,000 and promises to give him their bonds from #8 as collateral. They&#39;ll pay him back in one month. He agrees.<br />
10) MF Global buys $700,000 in bonds for $600,000<br />
<br />
You see what happened? They now have $3.5 million of bonds from $1 million. These bonds are currently worth $3.1 million. They owe the three of us $2.5 millon.<br />
<br />
Now watch<br />
<br />
11) The value of Italian bonds drops another 20%. That makes the value of the bonds about $2.48 million, a loss of 60% on their initial investment of $1 million.  That 2.48 is also less than they owe us.<br />
12) The month is up. Pat says give me my money back, this is too risky. They have to sell bonds to pay him back. <br />
13) Now they don&#39;t have collateral to get Enrique and Neal to loan them money, even if we wanted to.<br />
14) They now are bankrupt, owing more money than they have in assets. Enrique and I lose some money, and MF Global is out of business.<br />
<br />
Take that scenario and add 37 more levels of borrowers. A 5% loss now becomes a 200% loss on the original money!<br />
<br />
Does that makes any sense? <br><BR><font size=1>13:50 11-01-2011</font><BR><BR>I support the right of our troops to bear arms</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Max of Tat </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Max of Tat '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">So when you say buying debt you mean buying Italian and Spanish bonds?<br />
<br />
Is this correct?<br />
MF Global borrows from Decktech Global money ($1M) to buy bonds from Italy and Spain. Italy and Spain get the full $1M. MF Global goes bankrupt because it&#39;s not getting returns from Italy and Spain because they still have crappy economies. The bonds are sold for $.25M which is returned to Decktech Global. Now Decktech Global is out $.75M and their stability is suddenly in question.<br />
<br />
Am I close?<br />
